      "explanation": "The algorithm processes the path edge `<propagate_entry, val> -> <propagate_entry, val>` and propagates forward within `propagate`.\n\nAt `sink(val)`, the flow function passes `val` through (taint is not killed). The taint fact `val` reaches the sink call -- **this is where a taint violation would be reported**.\n\nContinuing past the sink call, `val` propagates to `propagate_exit`. When a path edge reaches a procedure's exit node, the algorithm creates a **summary edge**:\n\n> `propagate: val -> val` (if `val` is tainted at entry, it is tainted at exit)\n\nSummary edges are the key to IFDS efficiency. If `propagate` is called from another call site in the future, the algorithm can use the summary edge instead of re-analyzing the function body.\n\nThe algorithm also uses the summary edge to propagate facts back to the caller: since `t` was mapped to `val` at the call site, the summary result flows back to `main_exit`.",
