      "explanation": "The algorithm processes the remaining path edge `<main_entry, lambda> -> <main_exit, t>` which confirms that taint from `source()` survives to the end of `main`.\n\nThe worklist is now **empty** -- no new path edges can be discovered. The algorithm has reached a **fixed point**.\n\n**Results:**\n\n| Program Point | Dataflow Facts |\n|--------------|----------------|\n| `main:entry` | `{lambda}` |\n| `t = source()` | `{lambda, t}` |\n| `propagate(t)` | `{lambda, t}` |\n| `propagate:entry` | `{lambda, val}` |\n| `sink(val)` | `{lambda, val}` |\n| `propagate:exit` | `{lambda, val}` |\n| `main:exit` | `{lambda, t}` |\n\n**Taint violation detected:** The tainted fact `val` (derived from `t`, which originated at `source()`) is live at `sink(val)`. This confirms that untrusted data flows from `source()` through `propagate()` to `sink()` -- a potential security vulnerability.\n\nThe summary edge `propagate: val -> val` is now available for any future calls to `propagate` without re-analyzing its body.",
